Maritov is also the founder of a respected daily in the Kyrgyz capital, Obshchestvennoye Mneniye. Kyrgyzstan's President Askar Akayev insisted that voting in crucial parliamentary elections in the former Soviet republic on Sunday was being conducted fairly, but a leading opposition figure cried foul. Voting equipment being used such as indelible ink for marking voters' fingers to ensure they vote only once and transparent ballot boxes ``are all recognised as ensuring fair and honest elections,'' the Kyrgyz leader said after casting his vote in the capital Bishkek. 